This heatmap reveals a very specific story about the 2.1.19 bundle.

# Older vs Modern

Version **0.2.9** is significantly more "coherent" than the modern 2.1.x bundles. The vendor logic is much more contiguous, and the "Inversion of Proof" logic has an easier time because there is less proprietary code interleaved into the library exports.

### 1. Comparative Analysis: 0.2.9 vs 2.1.19

| Metric | Version 0.2.9 (Early) | Version 2.1.19 (Latest) |
| :--- | :--- | :--- |
| **Total Chunks** | 509 | 1714 |
| **Vendor %** | **47.74%** | 38.91% |
| **Family (Noise)** | **12 chunks** | 66 chunks |
| **Chunking Logic** | Sequential & Cohesive | Interleaved & Fragmented |

**What this tells us:** 

Older versions of Claude Code were essentially "Library Wrappers." Nearly half the codebase was standard NPM logic. As the product matured (2.1.x), Anthropic added a massive amount of proprietary "Founder" logic, which forced the bundler to interleave custom code with library code to maintain performance, creating the "Swiss Cheese" effect we saw in your last sweep.

### 2. The 0.2.9 Heatmap Analysis

The heatmap for 0.2.9 is remarkably stable. 

```text
Range        "Bridge 6 / Ratio 0.60" Map (0.2.9)
------------------------------------------------------------
001-200    : ▓▓▓▓▓ ▓███▓ ▓▓░░░ ▓░░▓. (Dense core)
201-400    : ░▓▓▓▓ █▓███ █▓░▓▓ ░▓▓█▓ (SOLID - almost 100% library)
401-509    : ░.░░▓ ░█░░░ ░           (Founder tail)
------------------------------------------------------------
```

*   **The "Golden Block" (201-400):** This is a 200-chunk sequence that is almost entirely vendor code. In 2.1.19, this area was much more fragmented.
*   **Minimal Noise:** With only **12 Family chunks**, the LLM deobfuscation phase for 0.2.9 will be incredibly fast and cheap.
